00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.170
even before scientific and
industrial revolutions.

00:06:08.170 --> 00:06:12.280
We did it, 20,000,
30,000 years ago.

00:06:12.280 --> 00:06:20.940
So language, which human
beings, or Homo sapiens used,

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:24.610
differed from language as a
homos, or even animals used.

00:06:24.610 --> 00:06:27.070
Animals can communicate.

00:06:27.070 --> 00:06:29.740
For example, they can
say that there is danger.

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:33.220
There is water there.

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:37.140
So some primitive things.

00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:39.500
Neanderthals, they
also used hot food,

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:42.000
so their brains also
were bigger than animals.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.310
And some say that even bigger
than Homo sapiens' brains.

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:50.320
But their language was still
this kind of primitive,

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:51.670
and very straightforward.

00:06:51.670 --> 00:06:55.120
What Homo sapiens created
was an abstract thinking,

00:06:55.120 --> 00:07:02.530
and language that used notions
and ideas that actually do not

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:03.590
exist.

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:05.230
So that was our strength.

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:09.010
So we used language
to describe things

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:11.140
that actually don't exist.

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:13.030
There is one very,
very interesting book--

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:14.090
you can read it.

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:19.180
It says, I think, Homo
sapiens and something,

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:20.080
I don't remember.

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:22.510
At the end I will
